INTRODUCTION

This data was collected from ten thousand university students and obtained from Kaggle. In this study, I examined the effect of the average of university students on other factors.

data_depression <- read.csv("C:\\Users\\furka\\Desktop\\R\\Student Depression_Lifestyle\\student_lifestyle_100k.csv")
View(data_depression)

STANDARD DEVIATION

First, I calculated the z-score for each column in the data individually. The lowest standard deviation was for physical activity, while the highest value was for time spent on social media.Standard deviations have not been calculated by group. Taking this into account, it is known that standard deviation values will differ according to student sections.

Regression Model Summary

A multiple linear regression model was fitted to examine the relationship between depression score and several lifestyle variables, including sleep duration, study hours, social media usage, physical activity, and stress level.

The overall model is statistically significant (F(5, 99994) = 367.7, p < 0.001), indicating that the predictors jointly explain a significant portion of the variance in depression scores. However, the explanatory power of the model is relatively low (R = 0.018), suggesting that most of the variation in depression is explained by factors not included in the model.

Key Findings

Sleep Duration has a small but statistically significant positive association with depression scores ( = 0.0044, p < 0.001).

Study Hours show a strong positive and highly significant effect ( = 0.027, p < 0.001), indicating that increased study time is associated with higher depression scores.

Social Media Hours are significantly and negatively associated with depression ( = 0.032, p < 0.001).

Stress Level has a statistically significant negative effect ( = 0.0034, p = 0.009).

Physical Activity does not have a statistically significant effect on depression in this model (p = 0.575).

The residuals are approximately symmetrically distributed around zero, and the residual standard error is 0.53, indicating moderate prediction error at the individual level.

Conclusion

While several predictors are statistically significant, the low R value suggests that depression is a multifactorial outcome, and lifestyle variables alone provide limited explanatory power. Further models incorporating psychological, biological, or social factors may improve predictive performance.
